	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />That has to be the craziest diagram I've ever seen.
<br />
<br />This is what people need to know:
<br />
<br />NOT 0 = 1
<br />NOT 1 = 0
<br />
<br />0 AND 0 = 0 
<br />0 AND 1 = 0
<br />1 AND 0 = 0
<br />1 AND 1 = 1
<br />
<br />0 OR 0 = 0
<br />0 OR 1 = 1
<br />1 OR 0 = 1
<br />1 OR 1 = 1
<br />
<br />0 XOR 0 = 0
<br />0 XOR 1 = 1
<br />1 XOR 0 = 1
<br />1 XOR 1 = 0
<br />
<br />NAND = AND with inverted (NOT) output
<br />NOR = OR with inverted output
<br />XNOR = XOR with inverted output
<br />
<br />If you're going to do digital design, then you should learn boolean algebra, but the above is all that's really necessary for bit masking.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
